A WHITE Kia truck hijacked on Friday, 31 December was found dumped on the very same day. Police spokesman Captain Frederick van Wyk said thanks to the hard work of K9 unit members with the provincial extortion task team, the delivery truck, which was hijacked in Philippi East in Cape Town, was recovered in Marikana squatter camp. “The members followed up information received on the whereabouts of a hijacked motor vehicle and the information led them to the Marikana squatter camp in Philippi East,” he said. Van Wyk said because of problems on the road, the team went around on foot gathering information before finding the truck abandoned between shacks. It was undamaged and just the battery had been taken. Van Wyk said no arrests had been made yet. Resident Luyanda Mda (45) said Marikana was a dangerous place. “I think the devil stays here. The things happening in this place will shock you. “People have lost many belongings and even taxi drivers are afraid of Marikana,” he said. “A good working relationship between residents and police officers is the only t Another resident said cops needed to arrest people found in possession of stolen goods. “It starts with us. We need to stop supporting criminals by buying their stolen goods. “They continue terrorising our communities because they know they have buyers and we need to stop that,” said the resident.